---
import GuideLayout from "../layouts/GuideLayout.astro";

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  mainEntity: [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      name: "How do I calculate my grade?",
      acceptedAnswer: {
        "@type": "Answer",
        text: "Add your earned points together and divide by the total possible points. If your class uses categories, use a weighted grade formula instead."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      name: "How do I calculate a weighted grade?",
      acceptedAnswer: {
        "@type": "Answer",
        text: "Multiply each category grade by its weight, add the results together, and divide by the total weight. You can also use a weighted grade calculator to do this automatically."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      name: "How do I know what I need on my final exam?",
      acceptedAnswer: {
        "@type": "Answer",
        text: "Use your current grade, your target grade, and your final exam weight to calculate the score you need. A final exam calculator can do this instantly."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<GuideLayout
  title="How to Calculate Your Grade (Step-by-Step Guide)"
  description="Learn how to calculate your grade step-by-step. Includes simple formulas, examples, and links to free grade calculators."
  slug="/how-to-calculate-your-grade"
  heroTitle="How to Calculate Your Grade"
  heroText="If you want to know your current average, your weighted grade, or what you need on your final, this guide will show you exactly how to calculate your grade step-by-step."
  faqSchema={faqSchema}
>
  <div class="card">
    <p>
      Many students ask questions like <strong>How do I calculate my grade?</strong>,
      <strong>How do weighted grades work?</strong>, and
      <strong>What do I need on my final?</strong> The answer depends on how your
      class is structured. This page breaks down the most common methods in a
      simple, practical way.
    </p>
  </div>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Method 1: Simple Grade Average</h2>
    <p>
      If all assignments are worth the same number of points, you can calculate
      your grade by adding your scores together and dividing by the total points
      possible.
    </p>

    <p><strong>Formula:</strong></p>
    <p>(Total Points Earned / Total Points Possible) x 100</p>

    <h3>Example</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Assignment 1: 18/20</li>
      <li>Assignment 2: 42/50</li>
      <li>Assignment 3: 90/100</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Total earned = 18 + 42 + 90 = 150
      <br />
      Total possible = 20 + 50 + 100 = 170
      <br />
      Grade = 150 / 170 x 100 = <strong>88.2%</strong>
    </p>

    <p>
      Try it here:
      <a href="/grade-calculator/">Grade Calculator</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Method 2: Weighted Grade Calculation</h2>
    <p>
      Some classes use weighted categories, which means different parts of the
      class count more than others. For example, tests might be worth more than
      homework.
    </p>

    <h3>Example</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Homework: 92% worth 20%</li>
      <li>Quizzes: 85% worth 30%</li>
      <li>Tests: 88% worth 50%</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Weighted grade =
      <br />
      (92 x 0.20) + (85 x 0.30) + (88 x 0.50)
      <br />
      = 18.4 + 25.5 + 44
      <br />
      = <strong>87.9%</strong>
    </p>

    <p>
      Try it here:
      <a href="/weighted-grade-calculator/">Weighted Grade Calculator</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Method 3: What You Need on Remaining Work</h2>
    <p>
      If you want to know what grade you need on your remaining assignments,
      projects, or final exam, you can work backward from your target grade.
    </p>

    <p>You need to know:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Your current grade</li>
      <li>Your target grade</li>
      <li>How much of the class is still left</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Try it here:
      <a href="/what-grade-do-i-need-calculator/">What Grade Do I Need Calculator</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Method 4: Final Exam Calculation</h2>
    <p>
      If your final exam counts as a specific percentage of your class, you can
      calculate the score you need by using your current grade, your target
      grade, and the final exam weight.
    </p>

    <p>
      Try it here:
      <a href="/final-exam-calculator/">Final Exam Calculator</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Method 5: GPA Calculation</h2>
    <p>
      GPA is different from a class percentage. GPA converts letter grades into
      grade points and averages them across all your classes.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>A = 4.0</li>
      <li>B = 3.0</li>
      <li>C = 2.0</li>
      <li>D = 1.0</li>
      <li>F = 0.0</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Try it here:
      <a href="/gpa-calculator/">GPA Calculator</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>How do I calculate my grade?</h3>
      <p>
        Add your earned points together, divide by the total possible points,
        and multiply by 100.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>How do I calculate a weighted grade?</h3>
      <p>
        Multiply each category average by its weight, add those values, and
        divide by the total weight.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>How do I know what I need on my final?</h3>
      <p>
        Use your current grade, target grade, and final exam weight to determine
        the required score. A final exam calculator makes this much easier.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</GuideLayout>
